<div id="review_3125784441" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3125784441" />
    <a title="SamOfKeenFables" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/69939447-samofkeenfables"><img alt="SamOfKeenFables" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1524549519p2/69939447.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3125784441?book_show_action=true">Jan 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="SamOfKeenFables" class="user" itemprop="url" name="SamOfKeenFables" href="/user/show/69939447-samofkeenfables">SamOfKeenFables</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3125784441" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11733144937350898808">While I am an absolute sucker for classic retellings, I have to say I didn&apos;t enjoy this nearly as much as I did the first book. I think I would have enjoyed it more had I read it when I was younger, which I believe was the intended audience. The book was supposed to be about Merlin&apos;s growth as a character and him learning from mistakes, but it seemed as if, to make this point more obvious, Barron made the character worse at the beginning of this book than he was through the entire first book. It</span>
  <span id="freeText11733144937350898808" style="display:none">While I am an absolute sucker for classic retellings, I have to say I didn't enjoy this nearly as much as I did the first book. I think I would have enjoyed it more had I read it when I was younger, which I believe was the intended audience. The book was supposed to be about Merlin's growth as a character and him learning from mistakes, but it seemed as if, to make this point more obvious, Barron made the character worse at the beginning of this book than he was through the entire first book. It was hard for me to get through the first third of the book because if how unbearable Merlin was. <br /><br />In addition, he didn't seem to really have to struggle at all to learn the souls of the songs, nor was he truly challenged at any point. To make up for this lack of challenge/believable danger, Merlin constantly laments that he probably won't finish his task, and the consequences if he doesn't. <br /><br />He also seems to keep half learning his lesson(s), then forgetting about them like five minutes later, and somehow it always seems like he never actually sees the folly in his ways, which makes any sort of character growth at the end seem half-hearted and temporary.<br /><br />I absolutely LOVED Shim from the first book and I think Barron tried to carry on that trope with Bumblewy, but I thought he really fell short, especially at the beginning.<br /><br />Okay it may not seem like I enjoyed the book, but I actually kind of did, at least the second half, though probably partly due to the Arthurian legend and Sword in the Stone references. Here's to hoping I like the next one more cuz I REALLY WANT TO.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11733144937350898808" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


