<div id="review_2273396541" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2273396541" />
    <a title="Mai" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34196958-mai"><img alt="Mai" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2273396541?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mai" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mai" href="/user/show/34196958-mai">Mai</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780142419205" href="/book/show/9705899-the-seven-songs">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2273396541" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17469651519290274848">This was one of my favorite books as a kid, and rereading it now, I enjoyed it just as much. Granted, I recognize some writing flaws, whether they were in tone or in the editing, but the story itself is just as good. I always thought the construction of Merlin&apos;s quest in this one, as well as the seven songs themselves, was really clever, and this reread did not let me down. <br/><br/>One thing in particular that I enjoyed that I think I didn&apos;t realize when I was younger was the references to the story of </span>
  <span id="freeText17469651519290274848" style="display:none">This was one of my favorite books as a kid, and rereading it now, I enjoyed it just as much. Granted, I recognize some writing flaws, whether they were in tone or in the editing, but the story itself is just as good. I always thought the construction of Merlin's quest in this one, as well as the seven songs themselves, was really clever, and this reread did not let me down. <br /><br />One thing in particular that I enjoyed that I think I didn't realize when I was younger was the references to the story of King Arthur (the Once and Future King) throughout the book. They were done really subtly, and set up and tie in this version of Merlin with the one we know really well. Another thing that I thought was an interesting choice on T.A. Barron's part was his characterization of the young Merlin. Not only is he really unsure of himself and his abilities, as would be expected for a fledgling wizard, but he's also still really immature and selfish. Unlike some stories, where the main character is always noble and makes the right decisions, the young Merlin makes a lot of mistakes. His character really grew from the beginning, when I repeatedly thought, 'Come ON, Merlin, you know better than that!' to the end, when he recognizes and accepts his shortcomings. Obviously, he still has a long way to go, but, as several characters point out to him in the book, he's well on his way. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17469651519290274848" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


